This pact transformed Guyana from a quasi-racial state, utilising race as a basis for political participation, to, as it promised at that time, a truly multi-ethnic society in which all races could equally benefit. In 1899, Guyana embarked on a process of political development which promised for its members a vision of a modern state based on the values of democracy. It is against this historical backdrop that I view the following Article.

- Joint Solutions for Guyana

It is estimated that the subject of ethnic hostility between the country's two major political parties, the People's National Congress Reform and the People's Progressive Party Civic originated with the signing of the Republican Constitution in 1961. Then a power struggle ensued to replace Cheddi Jagan as the first and only African President.

While the struggle between the Peoples' Progressive Party and the People's National Congress ended in 1964 with the election of Walter Rodney to lead the People's National Congress, acrimony again flirted with the country following the refusal of the PNC to recognise two of Jagan's Cabinet appointments.

In 1990 the situation again scaled to a new crisis when the ethnic bandwagon of the People's National Congress gathered momentum against the incoming presidency of Jagan. The ensuing struggle gave birth to the modern rebirth of the People's Progressive Party Civic
